06709nam a22009615i 9783110781922DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232024gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107819227 a10.1515/97831107819222doi  a(DE-B1597)617059  a(OCoLC)1409681804  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aB5409.Z3753bH38 2024 7aPHI0160002bisacsh04a199.632231 aYaqob, Zara, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Hatata Inquiries :bTwo Texts of Seventeenth-Century African Philosophy from Ethiopia about Reason, the Creator, and Our Ethical Responsibilities /cZara Yaqob, Walda Heywat; ed. by Ralph Lee, Mehari Worku, Wendy Laura Belcher. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2023] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (XXVII, 207 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tMaps and Figures -- tSimplified Spellings of Geʿez Words -- tAbbreviations -- tChronology of Events regarding the Hatata Inquiries -- tIntroduction to the Hatata Inquiries -- tManuscripts of the Texts -- tThe Authorship of the Hatata Inquiries -- tTranslation Principles -- tTranslation of the Hatata Zara Yaqob -- tTranslation of the Hatata Walda Heywat -- tAppendix 1: Chart of Differences between Abb 215 and Abb 234 of Hatata Zara Yaqob -- tAppendix 2: Scribal Intervention in Abb 215 and Abb 234 -- tContributors -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Hatata Inquiries are two extraordinary texts of African philosophy composed in Ethiopia in the 1600s. Written in the ancient African language of Geʿez (Classical Ethiopic), these explorations of meaning and reason are deeply considered works of rhetoric. They advocate for women’s rights and rail against slavery. They offer ontological proofs for God and question biblical commands while delighting in the language of Psalms. They advise on right living. They put reason above belief, desire above asceticism, love above sectarianism, and the natural world above the human. They explore the nature of being as well as the nature of knowledge, the human, ethics, and the human relation with the divine. They are remarkable examples of something many assume doesn’t exist: early written African thought. This accessible English translation of the Hatata Inquiries, along with extensive footnotes documenting the cultural and historical context and the work’s many textual allusions, enables all to read it and scholars to teach with it. The Hatata Inquiries are essential to understanding the global history of philosophy, being among the early works of rational philosophy. The book includes a translation by Ralph Lee with Mehari Worku and Wendy Laura Belcher of the Hatata Zara Yaqob and the Hatata Walda Heywat. The appendices by Jeremy R. Brown provide information on the scribal interventions in and the differences between the manuscripts of the two Hatatas. The book also includes a map, chronology, summary of the translation principles, and a discussion of the authorship debate about the Hatata Inquiries.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPhilosophy, Ethiopian. 4aafrikanische Autobiographie. 4aafrikanische Geistesgeschichte. 4aafrikanische Theologie. 4aäthiopische Studien. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh  aAfrican autobiography.  aAfrican intellectual history.  aAfrican theology.  aEthiopian studies.1 aBelcher, Wendy Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBelcher, Wendy Laura, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrown, Jeremy R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Jeremy, econtributor